#### Serializing and Deserializing with Avro:

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.producer.KafkaProducer;
import org.apache.kafka.common.serialization.StringSerializer;

public class OrderService {

    private final KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate;
    private final OrderRepository orderRepository;
    private final SchemaRegistryClient schemaRegistryClient;

    @Autowired
    public OrderService(KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate, OrderRepository orderRepository, SchemaRegistryClient schemaRegistryClient) {
        this.kafkaTemplate = kafkaTemplate;
        this.orderRepository = orderRepository;
        this.schemaRegistryClient = schemaRegistryClient;
    }

    public void createOrder(Order order) {
        try (var tx = new TransactionTemplate()) {
            tx.execute(status -> {
                // Save order in database
                Order savedOrder = orderRepository.save(order);

                // Create outbox message
                String payload = objectMapper.writeValueAsString(new OrderCreatedEvent(savedOrder));
                OutboxMessage outboxMessage = new OutboxMessage(
                    "order-created",
                    payload,
                    "PENDING"
                );
                orderOutboxRepository.save(outboxMessage);

                // Publish to Kafka with Avro serialization
                Integer id = schemaRegistryClient.register("order-created-value", OrderCreatedEvent.SCHEMA);
                kafkaTemplate.send(new ProducerRecord<>("order-created", savedOrder.getId(), payload));
                return null;
            });
        }
    }
}
```

### Summary

Combining the outbox pattern with Kafka transactions ensures that your system maintains consistency between database operations and message publishing. This approach provides a robust mechanism for handling distributed systems where reliability and fault tolerance are critical.

By following these steps, you can build a resilient and consistent order management system using Spring Boot, Kafka, and Confluent Schema Registry.

When dealing with consumer-side transactions in a Kafka-based system, especially when integrating with PostgreSQL, it's important to ensure that all database operations are consistent with the messages processed from Kafka. This can be achieved by using transactional consumers and coordinating these transactions with your PostgreSQL database.

Here’s how you can set up consumer-side transactions involving PostgreSQL:

### 1. Configure Consumer Transactions

First, configure your Kafka consumer to use transactional mode. This ensures that all operations (both Kafka consumption and database updates) are part of a single transaction.

#### Example Configuration:

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.ConsumerConfig;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class KafkaConsumerConfig {

    @Bean
    public Map<String, Object> consumerConfigs() {
        Map<String, Object> props = new HashMap<>();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "order-management-consumer-group");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, KafkaAvroDeserializer.class);

        // Enable auto-commit
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, false); // Disable auto-commit

        // Transactional consumer settings
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ISOLATION_LEVEL_CONFIG, "read_committed");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.MAX_POLL_RECORDS_CONFIG, 10);

        return props;
    }
}
```

### 2. Use TransactionAwareMessageListener

Spring Kafka provides `TransactionAwareMessageListener` to handle transactions across both Kafka and PostgreSQL.

#### Example Consumer Implementation:

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.ConsumerRecord;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.kafka.listener.TransactionAwareMessageListener;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component
public class InventoryConsumer implements TransactionAwareMessageListener<String, OrderEvent> {

    @Autowired
    private InventoryService inventoryService;

    @Override
    public void onMessage(ConsumerRecord<String, OrderEvent> record) {
        try {
            // Process the order creation event and adjust inventory accordingly
            inventoryService.adjustInventory(record.value());

            // Commit transaction
            consumer.commitSync(Collections.singletonMap(new TopicPartition(record.topic(), record.partition()), new OffsetAndMetadata(record.offset() + 1)));
        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.error("Failed to process order created event: " + record.toString(), e);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void onCompletion(ConsumerRecord<String, OrderEvent> record, Exception exception) {
        if (exception != null) {
            // Handle exceptions and retry logic here
            logger.error("Transaction failed for record: " + record.toString(), exception);
        } else {
            logger.info("Successfully processed record: " + record.toString());
        }
    }

    @Bean
    public ContainerProperties containerProperties() {
        ContainerProperties containerProps = new ContainerProperties("order-created");
        containerProps.setAckMode(ContainerProperties.AckMode.MANUAL_IMMEDIATE); // Commit immediately after processing
        return containerProps;
    }
}
```

### 3. Database Transaction Management

Ensure that your database operations are part of the same transaction as Kafka consumption.

#### Example Service Implementation:

