### Recap of EOS

Exactly-Once Semantics (EOS) ensures that each message is processed exactly once even in the presence of failures or restarts. In Flink, this involves configuring checkpointing and transactional modes to ensure consistency across Kafka producers, consumers, and database operations.

### Integrating EOS with Stream Processing Pipelines

To integrate EOS into your stream processing pipelines using Flink, follow these steps:

#### 1. Enable Checkpointing
Ensure that your Flink job is configured to enable checkpointing in exactly-once mode.

```java
import org.apache.flink.api.common.functions.MapFunction;
import org.apache.flink.streaming.api.CheckpointingMode;

public class OrderAnalyticsJob {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        final StreamExecutionEnvironment env = StreamExecutionEnvironment.getExecutionEnvironment();

        // Enable checkpointing with exactly-once mode
        env.enableCheckpointing(5000, CheckpointingMode.EXACTLY_ONCE);

        // Configure restart strategy
        env.getConfig().setRestartStrategy(RestartStrategies.fixedDelayRestart(
            3, // Number of restart attempts
            Time.seconds(10) // Delay between restarts in seconds
        ));

        Properties props = new Properties();
        props.setProperty("bootstrap.servers", "localhost:9092");
        props.setProperty("group.id", "order-analytics-consumer-group");

        FlinkKafkaConsumer<OrderEvent> kafkaConsumer = new FlinkKafkaConsumer<>(
            "order-created",
            new KafkaAvroDeserializationSchema<>(OrderEvent.class),
            props
        );

        DataStream<OrderEvent> orderEvents = env.addSource(kafkaConsumer);

        // Process the events (e.g., analytics, transformations)
        DataStream<Tuple2<String, Integer>> aggregatedOrders = orderEvents.map(new MapFunction<OrderEvent, Tuple2<String, Integer>>() {
            @Override
            public Tuple2<String, Integer> map(OrderEvent event) throws Exception {
                return new Tuple2<>(event.getProductId(), 1);
            }
        }).keyBy(0).sum(1);

        // Output the results (e.g., to a sink)
        aggregatedOrders.print();

        // Start the execution
        env.execute("Order Analytics Job");
    }

    public static class KafkaAvroDeserializationSchema<T> implements DeserializationSchema<T> {
        private final Class<T> type;

        public KafkaAvroDeserializationSchema(Class<T> type) {
            this.type = type;
        }

        @Override
        public T deserialize(byte[] message) throws IOException {
            return new GenericDatumReader<>(new Schema.Parser().parse(getLatestSchema()))
                .read(null, new BinaryDecoder(new SeekableByteArrayInputStream(message)));
        }

        private String getLatestSchema() throws Exception {
            // Fetch the latest schema from Confluent Schema Registry
            // Example: http://localhost:8081/subjects/order-created-value/versions/latest
            return "Your Avro Schema Here";
        }
    }
}
```

#### 2. Configure Transactional Consumers

Ensure that your Kafka consumers are configured to use transactional mode and coordinate transactions with PostgreSQL.

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.ConsumerConfig;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;

@Configuration
public class KafkaConsumerConfig {

    @Bean
    public Map<String, Object> consumerConfigs() {
        Map<String, Object> props = new HashMap<>();
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.BOOTSTRAP_SERVERS_CONFIG, "localhost:9092");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.GROUP_ID_CONFIG, "order-management-consumer-group");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.KEY_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, StringDeserializer.class);
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.VALUE_DESERIALIZER_CLASS_CONFIG, KafkaAvroDeserializer.class);

        // Enable auto-commit
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ENABLE_AUTO_COMMIT_CONFIG, false); // Disable auto-commit

        // Transactional consumer settings
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.ISOLATION_LEVEL_CONFIG, "read_committed");
        props.put(ConsumerConfig.MAX_POLL_RECORDS_CONFIG, 10);

        return props;
    }
}
```

#### 3. Use `TransactionAwareMessageListener` for Consumers

Ensure that your consumers use `TransactionAwareMessageListener` to handle transactions across both Kafka and PostgreSQL.

```java
import org.apache.kafka.clients.consumer.ConsumerRecord;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.kafka.listener.TransactionAwareMessageListener;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component
public class InventoryConsumer implements TransactionAwareMessageListener<String, OrderEvent> {

    @Autowired
    private InventoryService inventoryService;

    @Override
    public void onMessage(ConsumerRecord<String, OrderEvent> record) {
        try {
            // Process the order creation event and adjust inventory accordingly
            inventoryService.adjustInventory(record.value());

            // Commit transaction
            consumer.commitSync(Collections.singletonMap(new TopicPartition(record.topic(), record.partition()), new OffsetAndMetadata(record.offset() + 1)));
        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.error("Failed to process order created event: " + record.toString(), e);
        }
    }

    @Override
    public void onCompletion(ConsumerRecord<String, OrderEvent> record, Exception exception) {
        if (exception != null) {
            // Handle exceptions and retry logic here
            logger.error("Transaction failed for record: " + record.toString(), exception);
        } else {
            logger.info("Successfully processed record: " + record.toString());
        }
    }

    @Bean
    public ContainerProperties containerProperties() {
        ContainerProperties containerProps = new ContainerProperties("order-created");
        containerProps.setAckMode(ContainerProperties.AckMode.MANUAL_IMMEDIATE); // Commit immediately after processing
        return containerProps;
    }
}
```

#### 4. Ensure Database Transactions

Ensure that your database operations are part of the same transaction as Kafka consumption.

```java
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.jdbc.core.JdbcTemplate;

@Service
public class InventoryService {

    @Autowired
    private JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate;

    public void adjustInventory(OrderEvent event) {
        // Update inventory levels in PostgreSQL database
        String sql = "UPDATE inventory SET quantity = quantity - 1 WHERE product_id = ?";

        jdbcTemplate.update(sql, event.getProductId());
    }
}
```

#### 5. Configure Transaction Manager

Ensure that your Spring application is configured to use a transaction manager for both Kafka and PostgreSQL.

```java
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Bean;
import org.springframework.context.annotation.Configuration;
import org.springframework.jdbc.core.JdbcTemplate;

@Configuration
public class TransactionConfig {

    @Autowired
    private JdbcTemplate jdbcTemplate;

    @Bean
    public PlatformTransactionManager transactionManager() {
        return new DataSourceTransactionManager(jdbcTemplate.getDataSource());
    }

    @Bean
    public ConcurrentKafkaListenerContainerFactory<String, OrderEvent> kafkaListenerContainerFactory(
            KafkaTemplate<String, OrderEvent> kafkaTemplate,
            PlatformTransactionManager transactionManager) {

        ConcurrentKafkaListenerContainerFactory<String, OrderEvent> factory = new ConcurrentKafkaListenerContainerFactory<>();
        factory.setConsumerFactory(consumerFactory());
        factory.getContainerProperties().setAckMode(ContainerProperties.AckMode.MANUAL_IMMEDIATE);

        // Set up transaction management
        factory.setTransactionManager(transactionManager);

        return factory;
    }
}
```

### Summary

By integrating Exactly-Once Semantics (EOS) into your Flink stream processing pipelines, you ensure that each message is processed exactly once even in the presence of failures or restarts. This setup involves:

1. **Checkpointing**: Enable checkpointing with exactly-once mode.
2. **Transactional Consumers**: Configure consumers to use transactional mode and coordinate transactions across Kafka and PostgreSQL.
3. **TransactionAwareMessageListener**: Use `TransactionAwareMessageListener` for handling transactions in Flink jobs.
4. **Database Transactions**: Ensure database operations are part of the same transaction as Kafka consumption.

This ensures that your real-time data pipelines maintain strong consistency guarantees, providing reliable insights into order management systems and other critical applications.

